{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17503324","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17503324"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:58:51+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:58:51+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2012"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2012","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2012"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.53,0.13,0.24,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2012"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"42042"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2012","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2012"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2012"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"27007"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"73"},{"type":"tags","id":"1017"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"772"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10811"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10869"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"42042","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/42042"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EEmma, a 38-year-old woman, is diagnosed with colorectal cancer. Her father also had colorectal cancer, diagnosed when he was 40. She undergoes genetic testing which confirms a MSH2 gene mutation. Given Emma\u0027s increased risk of malignancy, surveillance for other cancers must be considered.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is Emma most likely to develop?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Urothelial cancer","Endometrial cancer","Gastric cancer","Ovarian cancer","Breast cancer"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis question discusses a patient with Lynch syndrome (LS), specifically the MSH2 gene mutation. Lynch syndrome is caused by an inherited mutation in one of four mismatch repair (MMR) genes: \u003Cem\u003EMLH1, MSH2, MSH6 and PMS2. \u003C/em\u003EThose with LS have elevated risks of several cancers at ages of onset lower than the general population. For this reason, surveillance is an important part of secondary prevention in those with Lynch syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThere is no known clinically relevant increase in risk of \u003Cstrong\u003Ebreast cancer\u003C/strong\u003E in those with LS. \u00a0Of the other four options, all of which have a higher lifetime risk in LS, \u003Cstrong\u003Eendometrial cancer\u003C/strong\u003E is the most common, with a 47% lifetime risk in those with a \u003Cem\u003EMSH2 \u003C/em\u003Egene mutation, and a 33% risk in all with LS. \u003Cstrong\u003EUrothelial cancer \u003C/strong\u003Ehas a 21% lifetime risk, \u003Cstrong\u003Egastric cancer \u003C/strong\u003Ea 4% lifetime risk, and \u003Cstrong\u003Eovarian cancer \u003C/strong\u003Ea 17% lifetime risk.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Lynch syndrome increases lifetime risk of several cancers \u2013 those with the highest lifetime risk are colorectal cancer and endometrial cancer."],"references":["Sepp\u00e4l\u00e4 TT, Latchford A, Negoi I, et al. European guidelines from the EHTG and ESCP for Lynch syndrome: an updated third edition of the Mallorca guidelines based on gene and gender. Br J Surg. 2021;108(5):484-498. doi:10.1002/bjs.11902","Cancer Institute NSW. MMR genes (Lynch syndrome) \u2013 risk management. eviQ. Updated August 13, 2021. Accessed January 28, 2024. https://www.eviq.org.au/cancer-genetics/adult/risk-management/1410-mmr-genes-lynch-syndrome-risk-management#website-resources"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"dat